Name: POH YONG LING (FU YONGLING)
Content:
Abit embarrassing to share but thought would be a good reminder to myself that 100% is possible, 100% of the time with massive actions. 

Had gotten my driving license back in 2014, but never drive much n somehow the longer I don‚Äôt drive, the more fear I have, n more resistant I had towards driving. 
Last year due to certain events, I set a new resolutions to be a safe n skilled driving. I signed up for refresher driving lessons with a private instructor but I was inconsistent in having the lessons n I didn‚Äôt have much practice. So I didn‚Äôt manage to achieve that goal. 

Fast forward to 2025, my new year resolutions remain the same to be a safe n skilled driver. 
N this year, I did something different. I went to rent car to practice driving. I visualize myself being a skillful driver. 
I got a close gf to agree to accompany me to practice driving. 

N today for the first time, I finally had the guts to drive Alfred n 2 kids from East to west to my sis place n back to the east safely. üòÜü§£

Thankful to Alfred @alfredtohlegacy for giving me tips n warning along the way n the kids for being such patient passengers by keeping quiet to let me focus on the road. So quiet that they fell asleep on the way back. üòù

Small achievement unlocked ‚ò∫Ô∏è

Name: ALVIN KEH
Content:
- GFriend's 10th Anniversary Concert (Part 2) -

The school bell rang.

For a moment, I thought I lost the bet as I didn't expect „ÄäGlass Bead„Äã to be the opening song to kickstart the 3 nights of concert.

Whether was it paying homage to„ÄäGo Go GFriend!„Äã , or simply being 1 of the "School Trilogy" songs, „ÄäMe Gustas Tu„Äãended up as the opening act.

As the concert progresses, I realized that this wasn't a trip to Seoul; but instead, a trip down the memory lane.

Just like every other Buddy, I too have a story with GFriend - one that is over a decade long.

It all started back in 2015......

I was barely 25.

I was 26 when I met GFriend as Mr. Pikachu for the very first time at their„ÄäL.O.L. Showcase„Äã in Singapore.

I was 27 when I made an impromptu trip to Seoul to attend my very 1st Fan Sign event & Music Show.

I was 28 when I travelled all the way to Seoul for 3 days just to attend both nights of „ÄäSeason of GFriend„Äã

I was 29 when I went for all 10 stops of „ÄäGo Go GFriend„Äã Asia Tour across 9 countries.

I was 30 when I last saw GFriend at a Fan Sign event in Seoul before Covid-19 restricted all our travelling plans.

I was 31 when GFriend made an announcement that they won't be renewing their respective contracts.

And then I made a wish.

"In the year 2025, I hope that GFriend will have a reunion for their 10th Anniversary"

I was 35 when it eventually came true.

Back to the present, at their concert, a video of their past MVs were played.

Before the start of the concert, I was prepared to cry; just like how I did when I attended SNSD's 10th Anniversary Fan Meet.

And then I realized, there wasn't any reason to.

As a Buddy, I managed to do everything that I wanted to - except for the fact that I missed all the events when they sang „ÄäNeverland„Äã 

Rather than being emotional about how we had a hiatus & reuniting 4 years later, I was actually grateful that I had an incredible 6 years with them.

From „ÄäSeason of Glass„Äãto „ÄäSeason of Memories„Äã, I spent 40 Seasons with #GFriend

GFriend might not be forever, but our story with GFriend will always shine brightly!

Name: GRACE TAN HAN YI
Content:
30 years on earth! I always had many milestones for this age, and well...

I dont have the relationship I want,
but I have the love I need.

I dont have the house I want, 
but I have the family I need. 

I dont have the money I want, 
but I have the freedom I need. 

I was a little sad to not have achieved all the forms of success I had wanted when I was in my 20s...but I realised what I do have is clarity of what's, and will continue to be, truly important to me for the rest of my life, and a good idea of how to spend the time I have on earth tending to these special things.

In my journey, I‚Äôve learned that true success isn‚Äôt just about the big wins. It‚Äôs in the quiet moments of appreciation.

One of the biggest reasons why my clients, prospects or people that I talk to tend NOT to invest is because they are afraid of the volatility and fluctuations in the market.

While understandable, that‚Äôs also the MAIN reason why most don‚Äôt reach their financial goals in life, on time :(

But no fear! In this post, I‚Äôll be going through the top 5 things you need to understand if you want to know how to almost always WIN in the stock market.

#1 UNDERSTAND ASSETS
Identify asset classes and their respective nature. Over time, due to various factors (supply & demand, companies grow bigger), there will be a general uptrend.

#2 UNDERSTAND VOLATILITY
Volatility refers to fluctuations in value.
Standard deviation is used to measure the spread of returns.

Historical records show that the S&P500 follows a reasonably normal distribution; symmetric around the mean.

#3 NORMAL DISTRIBUTION... SO WHAT?
ALL ABOUT PROBABILITY

A normal distribution is also a probability distribution.
Rule of thumb: 68% of the yearly returns tend to fall within 1 standard deviation of the average return, 95% tend to fall within 2 standard deviation.

#4 UNDERSTAND VOLATILITY WITH NORMAL DISTRIBUTION

Therefore, assets usually fluctuate beyond the average market returns (8-10%), for better or for worse.

It has been shown that the longer the time horizon, the smaller the standard deviation. 
*Disclaimer: Standard deviation is merely used as a gauge, not to limit the range of market returns.

#5 UNDERSTAND NET RETURNS

It's true investments are never guaranteed.
However, the compounding effect is cumulative. If an average bull market cycle generates a total return of 268%, and the market crashes by 33% the following year, will you consider this a net gain or a net loss?
*Disclaimer: Assuming that you are invested in a well-diversified portfolio.

The biggest secret is your time in the market rather than timing the market.

Name: TAN WEI LONG, ROYSTON
Content:
Happy Chinese New Year! Êñ∞Âπ¥Âø´‰πêÔºÅSitting on to cash from your red packet? üßßüßßHere is something for you to ponder.

Many people hold large amounts of cash, thinking it‚Äôs the safest way to protect their wealth. But the truth is, cash is a guaranteed way to lose money over time.

Here‚Äôs why:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Inflation Erodes Purchasing Power
Imagine keeping $100,000 in cash for 10 years with an average inflation rate of 3%. That money would only have the purchasing power of about $74,000 in today‚Äôs terms. The longer you hold onto cash, the less it buys.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Opportunity Cost
While your cash sits idle, investments in equities, real estate, or even bonds generate returns. Historically, the stock market has averaged 7-10% annually. Over decades, that‚Äôs a massive difference in wealth creation.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Negative Real Returns
Even high-yield savings accounts barely keep up with inflation. If your money earns 2% interest but inflation is 4%, you‚Äôre effectively losing 2% per year.

üí° So, what‚Äôs the solution?
Instead of hoarding cash, put it to work. A well-diversified investment strategy tailored to your goals can help grow your wealth and outpace inflation. Cash has its place for emergencies, but as a long-term investment? It‚Äôs a slow but certain loss.

How are you deploying your cash wisely? Let‚Äôs discuss. #sgwealthplanner #financialfreedom #generationalwealth

üç∂Sakedokoro Eizaburo @eizaburo_official the latest concept by the Shunsui Group. This new izakaya brings a refreshing take on Japanese drinking and dining culture.
 
Located inüìç Fortune Centre, Eizaburo recreates the retro charm of Japan‚Äôs shitamachi culture, known for its traditional working-class neighborhoods and warm hospitality. Embracing a no-frills concept, the restaurant uses disposable tableware and online ordering to keep costs low while maintaining quality.
 
Enjoy small plates such as:
Binchotan-grilled Yakitori from $2.90++
Fresh Sashimi and Sushi from $3.90++
Side dishes such as Potato Salad, Creamy Crab Croquette, and Wagyu Sagari Steak from $3.90++

Lunch highlights include towering Kaisen-dons, Unagi Bowls, and Curry Udon / Rice from $7.90++.
 
Raise a glass with drinks starting from $6.90 such as Ultra Fizzy Whisky Highball and Lemon Sour, Suntory Premium Malts Draft at $9.80++, Shochu bottles from $69++, and Junmai Daiginjo from $84++. Don‚Äôt miss signature drinks like Baisu Sour and Sake with Oden Soup.
 
To maintain Eizaburo‚Äôs image as a drinking spot, as well as its competitive prices, there are 9 commandments that are requested of diners to understand prior to their visit. These include rules such as a two-drink policy per person, 90-minute dining limit during peak hours and rules to ensure a comfortable dining experience for other diners.
 
Eizaburo offers 48 seats, including a private room for up to 12 guests (reservations from 8 pax). Time Sales will be offered once a day, at a random, surprise timing, featuring special dishes at unbeatable prices.
